1237–Afdød","1231–Male":"1231–Afdød","1210–Male":"1210–Afdød","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1334":"1334","about 1259":"omkring 1259","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanien","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanien","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Spanien"},"nl":{"1237–":"1237–Overleden","1237–Female":"1237–Overleden","1231–Male":"1231–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1334":"1334","about 1259":"circa 1259","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Spanje"},"en":{"1237–":"1237–Deceased","1237–Female":"1237–Deceased","1231–Male":"1231–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1334":"1334","about 1259":"about 1259","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fernández","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Jorge, Miguel, Fernando, Mario, Jesus, Pedro, Francisco.  Portuguese Ligia, Joao, Armanda, Godofredo, Wenceslao.","Spanish (<b>Fernández</b>): patronymic from the personal name   Fernando  . The surname (and to a lesser extent the variant   Hernandez  ) has also been established in southern Italy, mainly in Naples and Palermo, since the period of Spanish dominance there.","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the name in 1 above at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some Jewish descendants retained the surname that their families had adopted as Roman Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Fernando","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Luis, Orlando, Aida, Carlos, Jesusa, Rodolfo, Ruben, Adela, Alfredo, Alicia.  Indian Rohan, Lalith, Nimal, Rajiv, Sanjeeva, Shanthi, Anil, Anusha, Dushan, Kapila, Lakshman, Mallika.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Fernando</i>, a younger form of <i>Ferdinando</i> (see   Ferdinand  ). This surname is also found in southern Italy, mainly in Naples and Palermo, since the period of Spanish dominance there, and as a result of the expulsion of the Jews from Spain and Portugal at the end of the 15th century, many of whom moved to Italy. It is also common in western India and especially in Sri Lanka, where it was taken by Portuguese colonists in the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Mayor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Pedro, Agapito, Alberto, Cesar, Cosme, Javier, Jorge, Jose, Juan, Manuel, Orlando.","English (Lancashire): variant of   Mayer   1.","Spanish: nickname for an older man or a distinguishing epithet for the elder of two bearers of the same personal name, from <i>mayor</i> ‘older’, from Latin <i>maior (natus)</i>, literally ‘greater (by birth)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Morgado","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Abilio, Acacio, Armando, Mario, Edmundo, Eduardo, Miguel, Adolfo, Alejandra.  Portuguese Henrique.","Portuguese and Spanish: distinguishing name for the eldest son of a family, from Portuguese <i>morgado</i> ‘first-born, heir’, Late Latin <i>maioricatus</i>, a derivative of <i>maior</i> (see   Mayor   2)."]},{"name":"Mayer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Hans, Franz, Helmut, Wilhelm, Erwin, Gerhard, Heinz, Ilse, Lorenz, Wolfgang.","English (Staffordshire): post-medieval form of <b>Mear</b>, which is either a topographic name, from Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘pond, pool’ (Old English <i>mere</i>) or Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘boundary’ (Old English <i>(ge)mǣre</i>), or a habitational name from one or more of the many places with names derived from these terms, such as Mere (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Wiltshire), Meir in Caverswall (Staffordshire), and Meare (Somerset).","English: occupational name for a physician, from Old French <i>mire</i>, Middle English <i>mire</i>, <i>meir</i>, <i>meyre</i>, originally synonymous with   Myer  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mayor Fernández was born in 1237, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain as the daughter of Juan Fernández. She married Gutiérrez Armíldez de Toledo, Prior de la O. de San Juan in 1258, in Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain."},"et":{"1237–":"1237–Surnud","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","1231–Male":"1231–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1334":"1334","about 1259":"umbes 1259","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Hispaania"},"fi":{"1237–":"1237–Kuollut","1237–Female":"1237–Kuollut","1231–Male":"1231–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1334":"1334","about 1259":"noin 1259","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanja","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Espanja"},"fr":{"1237–":"1237–Décédée","1237–Female":"1237–Décédée","1231–Male":"1231–Décédé"